          "body": "Verses 10–13 are among the most precisely fulfilled prophecies in the entire book. The prediction has four specific elements: the prince will flee in darkness (12:12); he will escape through a hole in the wall (12:12); God will spread a net and catch him in a snare (12:13); he will be brought to Babylon but will not see it, and he will die there (12:13). The historical fulfillment is recorded in 2 Kings 25:3–7 and Jeremiah 39:4–7 and 52:7–11. Zedekiah fled Jerusalem at night through a gap in the wall (2 Kings 25:4). He was captured near Jericho, brought before Nebuchadnezzar at Riblah, watched his sons executed before his eyes, and then was blinded — after which he was bound and taken to Babylon, where he died. He was brought to Babylon; he did not see it. The paradox of verse 13 ('he will not see it, though he will die there') resolves only through the blinding. Commentators uniformly note that Ezekiel could not have known the blinding detail from mere political calculation. This is prophetic foreknowledge of a historically improbable specific outcome, delivered years before the event."
