          "title": "Closing every escape route — the second deferral proverb",
          "body": "Verses 26–28 address a more theologically nuanced evasion than the first proverb. The community is now saying not that visions fail, but that Ezekiel's visions are genuine — they simply apply to 'many years from now' and 'times far off' (12:27). This is the concession-and-defer strategy: grant the prophet's authority while eliminating his urgency. The intellectual move is sophisticated; it honors the prophet in theory while neutralizing him in practice. God's response in verse 28 is the chapter's most final statement: 'None of My words will be delayed any longer. Whatever word I speak will be performed.' The double negative ('none... no longer') closes the only remaining interpretive exit. There is no more time-buffer available. The word is going out; the net is already spread; the sign-act has already been performed. Daniel Block (NICOT) observes that the escalation from proverb one to proverb two shows a community progressively adjusting its evasions as each one is dismantled — a pattern of spiritual hardening that the chapter's framing term *meri* (rebellious) has already named."
